    <h2>üí° Tips</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Build everything with security and privacy in mind.</li>
        <li>Don't release on Fridays or before public holidays unless there is an <em>extremely good</em> reason for it.</li>
        <li>Monitor the program when you release something to production, so that you do not wake up to a panic.</li>
        <li>Have Continuity of Business (COB) procedures covering hardware, software, services', people and potentially other types of failures (keep them as standardized as possible).</li>
        <li>If service is down, either switch to something else, where possible, or provide clear communication that is down, why it is down and for how long (if that is known).</li>
        <li>Limit number of active tickets per agent (can vary, but 10 is probably the most that majority of people can handle more or less efficiently).</li>
        <li>Have enough people to avoid understaffing critical functions for prolonged time even when 2 people are missing (1 on vacation and 1 on sick leave).</li>
        <li>Encourage taking vacation days instead of hoarding them.</li>
        <li>Be careful with alerts, so that they do not become noise, that is being ignored.</li>
        <li>Encourage smaller iterative changes instead of big ones.</li>
        <li>Once an issue is fixed explore ways to prevent recurrence in mid- and long- terms (create items in backlog, if required).</li>
        <li>Try to consider scaling of the solutions in time or at least with ability to handle sudden influxes (during season events, for example).</li>
        <li>Promote learning of new things inside the company, both about the product and related areas of knowledge.</li>
        <li>If you realize that you are no longer able to support the product (or a feature), find ways to hand it over to the community, in case someone else would be willing to (for example, open source the code, release SDKs or binaries).</li>
        <li>Have regularly updated onboarding trainings for new hires (bonus points if they are gamified).</li>
        <li>Security and privacy related issues should always take the highest priority.</li>
        <li>Keep calm and carry-on: cool head is what solves the problems, that hot heads have created, so punch some boxing dummy and approach everything logically.</li>
        <li>Do try to use eco-friendly solutions and generally be mindful about environment.</li>
    </ul>
